        I think basically to cut a long story short what the charts reflect now are what we were doing in the 70's and 80's when everytime our needle touched the vinyl record and we played the song we were into at that moment is the same as a play today on Spotify.
        The only difference is once we spent our money on a single it didnt contribute to further chart positions regardless if we played it to death or not.
        So that meant new material kept coming into the charts, keeping it much more exciting, and the turn over was more productive.
        Hence why I think streaming has killed music as we know it. The charts are stagnant.

        The charts are stagnant these days of streaming and I will explain in my opinion why.
        If we rewind when we actually bought a vinyl single or CD single and those formats reigned in the charts, fans bought a single they liked on a physical single and that was it, they didnt need to keep listening to it anywhere else they just played as often as they wanted to the vinyl single or whatever which meant there was room for something new to keep entering the charts
        Very rarely did a single last for 11 weeks such as Ed Sherran has recently done because most people have heard it on the radio and bought it by now.
        But in the world of streaming these days people seem to only use streaming platforms to listen to music via apps like Spotify so compared to playing something thats already purchased they keep a song on loop on Spotify and this happens all over the country keeping a song in the charts for a ridiculously long time outstaying its welcome compared to keeping the charts fresh as they used to be and should be.
        And I think this seriously needs to be looked into and adjusted in some way.
        That coupled with the fact streaming alienates older artists from having hits in the first place has made in my opinion the charts a sadder place. And I been following the pop charts for over 45 years. And the last 5 or 6 years I'd say has been unbearable to try and follow or get enthusiastic about.

        Yeah but ABBA are the biggest band in the world, I was expecting their new singles to be number 1. I think had they were released on physical formats they would be number 1 easily. I think number 9 was poor, and people were forced to stream the songs as their only way to listen to them, thats my belief anyway.
        The only reason Elton is having a hit is by piggy backing off Dua Lipa. His solo hits dried up years ago.
        In the physical age there was a quicker turn over of artists because once people bought the single they like they just play it ss much as they like, the sale has already done its job in terms of chart position, so they are already looking forward to next weeks releases.
        Streaming has greatly slowed this process down from what I can see in the top 100, some of the songs have been hovering around there for months in some cases over a year simply because people are using Spotify etc as their player, which in the old days would have been someone's record player, or cd player, and then mp3 player.
        It speaks for itself if you think about it, imagine if Spotify was the only place on earth to listen to music, the charts would just be an exaggeration of how its ended up now and become even more stagnant. Music as we know it would be dead and buried.
        We need a healthier more balanced charts which includes other formats that are priced equally across the board.
        Streaming is dominating other formats and alienating older artists via its cheap subscription.
        Obviously the majority of people would opt for listening to music as cheaply as possible, but they are ripping off the artists they claim to be a fan of rather than buy their physical product. This also has been well documented by artists such as Nile Rogers, Simon LeBon, Roger Daltrey, just to name a few, all claiming that streaming is ripping off the artists.
        Thats why I think it will kill off music completely very soon if a shake up isnt done soon.
        They either need to make how we listen to streaming services priced more fairly and in line with physical formats, or greatly reduce the price of physical formats.

        WEEKLY CHART REVIEW (01/10/2021 07/10/2021)

        (Negative)

        1) Bad Day is refusing to go away! So much for me hoping the hype for this would completely die this week. Yeah, I didnt have the same level of hate for this that I did last week somehow, but that still doesnt mean its terrible!

        2) Does anyone else find that Radio 1 always seem to play the same songs every week of those that arent inside the Top 10, e.g. Clash, Stay, Meet Me At Our Spot, If You Really Love Me [How Will I Know], Drive, Wasted, Black Magic, Take My Breath, etc.? I honestly think most of these songs are awesome, but what annoys me is the lack of variety in the chart show every week! Seriously, I swear theyre just pretending that Visiting Hours doesnt exist at this point & ultimately, I feel like Im just listening to a standard radio show than the weekly chart countdown at this point & it never used to be like that, even a few months ago.

        (Mixed)

        1) Ed Sheeran now sets a new personal best in terms of consecutive weeks at #1 (14). I know I generally like him as an artist more than most of this community, but even then, there are much better singles in his discography that he couldve done this with, e.g. Lego House, Castle On The Hill, Galway Girl etc.! Why Bad Habits & Shivers of all songs?

        2) My Universe debuted in the Top 3 with dominant sales! Honestly, I wasnt sure where my thoughts sat with this song when I first heard it & a week, my opinion on it only hasnt changed. I completely understand the hype, especially from fans of these kind of pop ballads; I appreciate how sweet the lyrics are, where a couple who are being doubted by others for being completely different people to one another are determined to overshadow all of the discriminatory views from the haters & put their love for each other first, Chris Martins cries in the hook further inject the passion into this & yet it still feels generally like a Coldplay song because of how much of it is primarily soft, alternative rock instrumentation. As for BTS, Jungkooks silky upper register is a surprisingly good fit to where the production is toned down a little, even if I do feel that j-hope & SUGA couldve given us a bit more of a dynamic performance in the bridge! I think my larger issue comes with some of the bizarre mixing thats going on here, particularly the robotic vocal pressing that randomly & abruptly appears halfway through the song (something youd expect more from a throwaway Daft Punk single) & the choppy breakdown in the final 30 seconds for the outro just didnt work at all, especially when the transition into it was so messy anyway. Thats why its not in the positive section for me yet, because while its a mostly fun & admittedly cute song, it had almost all the ingredients to be something truly amazing & even with 11 members on this song, it sadly still didnt get there for me! I respect the idea, but lets be honest, we know that both BTS & Coldplay are capable of showing off their talents far better than what weve heard here.

        3) While Im always disappointed to see Taylor take massive falls in the singles chart like she did today, I wasnt even expecting Wildest Dreams [Taylors Version] to last more than one week inside the Top 40, so the fact that Radio 1 actually played it on the chart show today was a really pleasant surprise for me!

        (Positive)

        1) Love Nwantiti broke the Top 5 & is now a hit almost everywhere in the world following five different remixes of it, as well as gaining a lot of virality on TikTok! You know when I said last week that this was far from my favourite Afrobeats hits? Im almost tempted to take that back! This keeps giving me warm, summery vibes even though were in the spell of terrible autumnal weather & I honestly cant say that about a lot of R&B or dancehall hits lately. I think if this keeps growing like it is now for much longer or a popular mainstream artist hops on it, then as long as Ed doesnt have any more tricks up his sleeve to boost the anticipation of =, Id say that this is the most likely song to go to #1 out of any thats in the charts right now!

        2) Love Tonight is almost Top 20 really? Okay, I knew a David Guetta remix had been propelling the success behind this for weeks now, but I thought it was on permanent ACR for the original version being over three years old, so I was really surprised to hear that it got a manual reset back to the normal streaming ratio after a request by their record label to OCC, since you dont typically see that happen for throwbacks like this that take a while to gain some recognition! Anyway, no complaints about it whatsoever, the song is absolutely remarkable, haha. I love the male & female call & response lines in the verses, proving within literally seconds that the singers here have stunning chemistry between them! Theyre also part of the choir in the hook who together sound absolutely euphoric over the melodic 80s-style electronica & thumping bass beat. The saxophone that peppers around the verses & outro also adds to the snazziness here! Honestly, Shouse have been able to crack the tough formula of making an EDM banger that would go off in clubs both today & from about 40 years ago. I cant think of many dance hits in 2021 that will have a massive sense of nostalgia in many decades to come, we all know that & even massive fans of the genre like myself would probably admit to it, but this might be an exception to the rule! I really adore this & seriously, if youre into upbeat party anthems & you havent heard this one yet, please check it out. You wont regret it!

        3) Meet Me At Our Spot & If You Really Love Me [How Will I Know] both made small gains! Regarding the latter, I think David Guetta did Whitney Houstons classic more justice than Clean Bandit did (their remix of it was unfortunately disappointing for me).

        4) Better Days is still growing nicely! I have a ton of respect how motivational & hopeful the lyrics are in this. Im so glad that the UK fell in love with another Dermot Kennedy single!

        5) Life Goes On by Oliver Tree didnt enter the Top 40 after all! I already had a rant prepared about this, so thank goodness the British public saved me both time & sanity from not having to post it here, haha.
